name: Diethyl 3,4-dimethylthieno[2,3-b]thiophene-2,5-dicarboxylate
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-3904
Reason: 3,4-dimethylthieno[2,3-b]thiophene-2,5-dicarboxylate has a melting point that is influenced by its structural components relative to the base of benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C. The basic unit we can compare to is the piperidine ring, which has a melting point of around 30 degrees Celsius. The additional functional groups and structural features in diethyl 3,4-dimethylthieno[2,3-b]thiophene-2,5-dicarboxylate will affect its melting point: (1) Two phenyl groups, which could each add approximately +20 due to the increase in molecular weight and rigidity of the structure; (2) The tertiary butyl group (C(C)C) is a bulky group which could add about +10 due to steric hindrance and increasing the molecular volume; (3) The piperidine ring (N1CCCC1) and 1-ethyl-4-methylenepiperidine moiety may both add roughly +20 each due to adding more rigid ring structures and making the molecule more compact; (4) The thieno[2,3-b]thiophene-2,5-dicarboxylate group introduces a significant dipole, increasing intermolecular forces and melting point by approximately +50°C. Summing these modifications gives us an estimated melting point shift.
